using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        int N = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
        List<int> A = new List<int>();

        string[] input = Console.ReadLine().Split(' ');
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        {
            A.Add(int.Parse(input[i]));
        }

        List<int> remainingElements = ApplyOperations(A);

        Console.WriteLine(string.Join(" ", remainingElements));
    }

    static List<int> ApplyOperations(List<int> A)
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < A.Count; i++)
        {
            int sum = 0;
            for (int j = 0; j < A.Count; j++)
            {
                sum += A[j];
            }
            int avg = sum / A.Count;

            List<int> newA = new List<int>();
            for (int j = 0; j < A.Count; j++)
            {
                if (A[j] >= avg)
                {
                    newA.Add(A[j]);
                }
            }
            A = newA;
        }

        return A;
    }
}
```

This solution reads the input, adds the elements to a list, and then applies the operations one by one. The `ApplyOperations` function calculates the average and removes all elements smaller than the average in each iteration. Finally, the remaining elements are printed.

Here is a C# code to solve the Collatz conjecture:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        int N = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());

        string sequence = CollatzConjecture(N);

        Console.WriteLine(sequence);
    }

    static string CollatzConjecture(int N)
    {
        string sequence = N.ToString();

        while (N > 1)
        {
            if (N % 2 == 0)
            {
                N = N / 2;
            }
            else
            {
                N = N * 3 + 1;
            }

            sequence += " " + N.ToString();
        }

        return sequence;
    }
}
```

This code reads the input integer `N`, then calls the `CollatzConjecture` function to generate the sequence. The function starts with `N` and repeatedly applies the Collatz conjecture rules until `N` becomes 1. The generated sequence is stored in a string and returned. Finally, the sequence is printed on the console.

Here's a solution in C# to compute the sum of the ASCII values of the upper-case characters in a given string:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string s = Console.ReadLine();

        int sum = ComputeAsciiSum(s);

        Console.WriteLine(sum);
    }

    static int ComputeAsciiSum(string s)
    {
        int sum = 0;

        foreach (char c in s)
        {
            if (Char.IsUpper(c))
            {
                sum += (int)c;
            }
        }

        return sum;
    }
}
```

This code reads the input string `s`, then calls the `ComputeAsciiSum` function to calculate the sum of the ASCII values of the upper-case characters in the string. The function iterates over each character in the string, checks if it is an upper-case character using the `Char.IsUpper()` method, and if it is, it adds its ASCII value to the sum. Finally, the sum is printed on the console.

Here's a C# solution to determine the minimum number of key strokes required to type a given string on a QWERTY keyboard:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string s = Console.ReadLine();

        int strokes = ComputeKeyStrokes(s);

        Console.WriteLine(strokes);
    }

    static int ComputeKeyStrokes(string s)
    {
        int strokes = 0;

        foreach (char c in s)
        {
            if (Char.IsLower(c))
            {
                strokes += 1;
            }
            else if (Char.IsUpper(c))
            {
                strokes += 1;
            }
            else if (c == ' ')
            {
                strokes += 1;
            }
        }

        return strokes;
    }
}
```

This code reads the input string `s`, then calls the `ComputeKeyStrokes` function to calculate the minimum number of key strokes required to type the string on a QWERTY keyboard. The function iterates over each character in the string and increments the `strokes` counter based on the character type. Lowercase letters, uppercase letters, and spaces all require one key stroke each. Finally, the total number of strokes is printed on the console.

Here's a C# solution to decode a given string representing a birthday:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string DT = Console.ReadLine();

        string Birthday = DecodeBirthday(DT);

        Console.WriteLine(Birthday);
    }

    static string DecodeBirthday(string DT)
    {
        string[] parts = DT.Split('-', '/');

        string day = DecodePart(parts[0]);
        string month = DecodePart(parts[1]);
        string year = DecodePart(parts[2]);

        return $"{day}-{month}-{year}";
    }

    static string DecodePart(string part)
    {
        string decodedPart = "";

        for (int i = 0; i < part.Length; i += 2)
        {
            int index = int.Parse(part.Substring(i, 2));
            char letter = (char)('A' + index);
            decodedPart += letter;
        }

        return decodedPart;
    }
}
```

This code reads the input string `DT`, then calls the `DecodeBirthday` function to decode the string and return the decoded birthday. The function splits the string into three parts based on the occurrence of "-" or "/", then calls the `DecodePart` function to decode each part separately. The `DecodePart` function iterates over the characters in the part, takes each two-character substring as an index, converts it to an integer, then adds the corresponding letter to the decoded part using the ASCII value. Finally, the decoded day, month, and year are concatenated with "-" or "/" respectively, and returned as the decoded birthday.

Here's a C# solution to convert a given number to its binary representation:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        int N = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());

        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        {
            int X = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());

            string binary = ConvertToBinary(X);

            Console.WriteLine(binary);
        }
    }

    static string ConvertToBinary(int X)
    {
        if (X == 0)
        {
            return "0";
        }

        string binary = "";

        while (X > 0)
        {
            binary = (X % 2) + binary;
            X = X / 2;
        }

        return binary;
    }
}
```

This code reads the input integer `N`, which represents the number of numbers to convert. It then iterates `N` times, reading each number `X` and calling the `ConvertToBinary` function to convert it to its binary representation. The function handles the edge case of `X` being 0 by returning "0". For other numbers, it performs the conversion by repeatedly taking the remainder when dividing `X` by 2 and adding it to the front of the `binary` string, and then dividing `X` by 2. Finally, the binary representation is printed on each line.

